elements.content: Novel Cu(I) complexes containing a μ2-η2,η2-type benzoquinone ligand have been synthesized and crystallographycally characterized. These complexes are synthesized by the redox reaction of a copper−quinonoid pair and may indicate a significant intermediate in the Cu−BQ catalytic system. Moreover, this study is regarded as one of the good examples in the Cu(I)−olefin family of enhanced π-back-donation.

elements.content: Quinonoid compounds are one of the most versatile redox-active organic molecules and have played a pivotal role in electron- and proton-transfer reactions. Among compounds including these molecules, a combination of two redox pairs, copper(I)/copper(II) and p-benzoquinone (BQ)/hydroquinone (HQ), is the most interesting due to its biological roles and catalytic activities in addition to its rich electrochemistry. Although BQ is a potentially bidentate olefin ligand to provide multinuclear complexes (Scheme ), copper(I)−BQ complexes reported thus far are very rare, which are expected to afford not only important information for intermediates in the Cu−BQ catalytic system but also rich redox chemistry based on a variety of formal oxidation states for both the metal centers and the ligand moiety. Herein we report the synthesis and structures of a novel copper(I) complex family containing a μ2-η2,η2-type BQ ligand, [CuI 2(syn-μ2-η2,η2-BQ)(OAc)2] (1), {[CuI 2(anti-μ2-η2,η2-BQ)Cl2(py)2]} n (2), and {[CuI 2(syn-μ2-η2,η2-BQ)(4,4‘-bpy)]·0.5HQ} n (3), where compound 1 and 3 are first examples of syn-type Cu2−BQ complex.
elements.clean_text: Quinonoid compounds are one of the most versatile redox-active organic molecules and have played a pivotal role in electron- and proton-transfer reactions. Among compounds including these molecules, a combination of two redox pairs, copper(I)/copper(II) and p-benzoquinone (BQ)/hydroquinone (HQ), is the most interesting due to its biological roles and catalytic activities in addition to its rich electrochemistry. Although BQ is a potentially bidentate olefin ligand to provide multinuclear complexes (Scheme ), copper(I)-BQ complexes reported thus far are very rare, which are expected to afford not only important information for intermediates in the Cu-BQ catalytic system but also rich redox chemistry based on a variety of formal oxidation states for both the metal centers and the ligand moiety. Herein we report the synthesis and structures of a novel copper(I) complex family containing a μ2-η2,η2-type BQ ligand, [CuI 2(syn-μ2-η2,η2-BQ)(OAc)2] (1), {[CuI 2(anti-μ2-η2,η2-BQ)Cl2(py)2]} n  (2), and {[CuI 2(syn-μ2-η2,η2-BQ)(4,4‘-bpy)]⋅0.5HQ} n  (3), where compound 1 and 3 are first examples of syn-type Cu2-BQ complex.

elements.content: A key to success in the synthesis of the syn-type Cu2−BQ complex 1 is the use of dimetallic copper(II) acetate, [CuII 2(OAc)4(H2O)2], and HQ as oxidant and reductant, respectively. The reaction of [CuII 2(OAc)4(H2O)2] with HQ (1.2 equiv) in ethanol affords a red solution. Slow evaporation of the ethanol affords 1 as air-stable red plates (yield 95%). The anti-type complex 2 is obtained by the replacement of two bridging acetate anions of 1 with chloride anions. The addition of pyridine and chloroform to the ethanol solution of 1 affords 2 as red prisms in one month (41%), where chloroform acts as a supplier of chloride anions. On the other hand, a coordination polymer 3 was successfully obtained by linking 1 with 4,4‘-bipyridine as a linear bidentate linker. The reaction of 1 with 4,4‘-bipyridine and excess HQ results in the formation of 3 as air-stable red plates (35%). All compounds were characterized by the X-ray crystallography.

elements.content: The molecular structure of 1 is shown in Figure . The BQ ligand coordinates two Cu atoms in a syn-μ2-η2,η2 fashion. The two Cu atoms are bridged by one BQ and two acetates, forming a dicopper core (Cu2). The axial positions of the Cu2 core are occupied by the weakly coordinated oxygen atoms from the neighboring Cu2 units (Cu1−O6‘ 2.273(9) Å, Cu2−O1‘ ‘ 2.294(8) Å). It is worth noting that the alkenic bonds of the BQ of 1 (C2−C3 1.42(2) Å, C5−C6 1.37(2) Å) are significantly longer than that of the free BQ (1.322 Å). Measurements of the magnetic susceptibility of 1 at ambient temperature show diamagnetism, which corresponds to monovalent copper cations.

elements.content: Figure shows the molecular structure of 2, where the BQ ligand sits in an anti-μ2-η2,η2 fashion. The Cu center has a distorted tetrahedral environment with the two chloride atoms, one nitrogen atom, and an alkenic moiety from the BQ. The chloride anion also bridges the two Cu ions, forming a two-dimensional layer (Figure ). The alkenic bonds of the BQ of 2 (1.383(3) Å) are also longer than that of the free BQ (1.322 Å).

elements.content: Molecular Structure of2.

The molecular structure of 3 is shown in Figure . The Cu2 dimetallic unit is constructed in a way similar to that of 1. Like 1 and 2, the alkenic bonds of the BQ of 3 (C2−C3 1.37(2) Å, C5− C6 1.41(2) Å) are longer than that of the free BQ (1.322 Å). In the case of 3, the axial positions of the Cu2 unit are occupied by nitrogen atoms from the 4,4‘-bpy to construct a one-dimensional coordination chain. To satisfy the crystal packing, one free HQ is contained per two Cu2 units, hydrogen-bonded to carboxylate groups from the bridging acetate. (Figure ).

One of the remarkable features of these Cu−BQ complexes is observed in their 13C NMR studies. The 13C CPMAS NMR spectra show the extremely large upfield shifts of the alkenic carbon atoms of the BQ (87.31 ppm for 1, 95.46 ppm for 2, and 88.72 ppm for 3) compared to that of the metal-free BQ (136.55 ppm, CDCl3 solution), indicative of the bond-order decrease in the alkenic bond, consistent with the trend in the crystallographic results. There have been to date some examples of 13C NMR studies for copper(I)−olefin complexes, in which the spectra show the upfield shifts of the alkenic carbon atoms compared with those of metal-free olefin. However, the magnitude of the upfield shifts for common copper(I)−olefin complexes are small because of weak π-back-donation from Cu(I) to the olefin ligand. To the best of our knowledge, these Cu−BQ complexes show the largest upfield shifts on coordination for the alkenic carbon atoms of the copper(I)−olefin complex (Δδ = −49.24 ppm for 1, −41.09 ppm for 2, and −47.83 ppm for 3). Two electron-withdrawing carbonyl groups on each olefin bond in the BQ ligand enhance π-back-donation, which could be a principal reason for the large upfield shifts.

elements.content: Compound 1 is soluble in polar organic solvents, such as methanol, ethanol, acetonitrile, and THF. The 13C NMR chemical shifts of 1 in CD3OD are in good agreement with those in solid state and show 87.14 ppm chemical shift of the alkenic carbon atoms (Δδ = −49.41 ppm). The 1H NMR spectrum of 1 in CD3OD shows two peaks (δ = 4.925 (4H) and 1.819 (6H)), corresponding to hydrogen atoms from BQ and AcO-, respectively. The chemical shift of hydrogen atoms of π-coordinated BQ also shows the extremely large upfield shift compared to that of the metal-free BQ (δ = 6.800 ppm in CDCl3 solution, Δδ = −1.875 ppm), corresponding to the results of 13C NMR.

elements.content: One of the best methods to elucidate the electronic structure is density functional theory (DFT) calculation on the discrete model compound based on the X-ray structure. However, 1 is not suitable for such a model compound because two adjacent Cu2 cores are too close in the crystal packing with the result that the axial positions of the Cu2 core are occupied by oxygen atoms from the neighboring Cu2 units. Meanwhile, in the crystal of 3, the axial positions of the Cu2 core are occupied by nitrogen atoms from 4,4‘-bpy (Figure ), and there is no appreciable interaction between the two nearest-neighbor Cu2 cores. Accordingly, we carried out the DFT calculation on the model compounds [Cu2(syn-μ2-η2,η2-BQ)(OAc)2(py)2] (3‘).

elements.content: The frontier orbitals for 3‘ show that the HOMO is a σ* orbital of the Cu2 core; the LUMO is an antibonding orbital formed from a π* orbital of the BQ and a δ orbital of the Cu2 core and mainly localized on the π* orbital (Figure S1 in Supporting Information). The notable results of this calculation are the molecular orbitals for the HOMO-1 and -2, which obviously show the π-back-donation from δ or δ* orbitals of the Cu2 unit to π* orbitals of the BQ. On this basis, the trend in upfield shifts of 13C NMR of 3 is well reproduced by the calculation of the 13C NMR on 3‘ (Figure S2 in Supporting Information).

elements.content: This study represents the syntheses and structures of Cu(I) complexes containing the μ2-η2,η2-type benzoquinone ligand, which are synthesized by the redox reaction of a copper−quinonoid pair and may indicate a significant intermediate in the Cu−BQ catalytic system. Above all, we successfully synthesized the one-dimensional coordination polymer containing the Cu2−BQ cores, which is our first step toward the construction of microporous coordination network with reactive or catalytic sites. Moreover, this study is regarded as one of the good examples in Cu(I)−olefin families with the enhanced π-back-donation.
